metadata.name: Pixel Heartbeats (animated) #192
metadata.description:
A uniquely generated animated pixel art piece, reminiscent of a beating heart. Based on a 2013 gif piece of mine, the rigidness of the collection's extra large pixels meet organic generative shapes and natural feeling rhythms, resulting in a mood somewhere between the biological and digital worlds.


Each piece features a unique, sharply rendered generative pixel art with a special heartbeat animation rhythm. The collection also includes exciting color and resolution rarity variations.


--


60% Standard red heart colors
35% Unique rare color variants
5% Special "Shiny" animated color


45% low-fi pixel art animations
45% mid-fi pixel art animations
10% hi-fi pixel art animations


Thanks for stopping by and hope you enjoy!

metadata.name: Gradient Ascent #5
metadata.description:
Generates a lo-fi sci-fi landscape and applies effects to the result. Most are 2:3 portrait aspect ratio with a smaller chance for landscape or square.

Several cool bonus features are included. Click to draw the image without post processing which can also be downloaded. The unique effect for each iteration can be applied to any image, just drag and drop! There are also URL commands included for advanced users.

Controls

Click = Toggle Processing
Drag & Drop = Process an Image
1 = Toggle processing
2 = Increase resolution
3 = Save as a png

URL Commands

width and height = Change the output size
hd = Set to 1 to show HD by default

Programmed in Vanilla JavaScript by KilledByAPixel
Code and Outputs are Copyright (C) 2022 Frank Force
Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Quad-Overlaps #37
metadata.description:
A simple study in color and shape overlap by Nate Donato. This collection features a large number of generative quadrilaterals and a unique painting algorithm of tinting select overlapping sections, combining to produce a wide range of unique outputs that toe a visually pleasing line between order and chaos. Inspired by early computer art pioneers such as Georg Nees and Vera Molnár, the piece builds on their work exposing how even simplistic algorithms can lead to exciting and unexpected results.


13 possible color schemes (some with random tint variations). Multiple draw modes.
Chances for extra jumbled shapes or other rare variants.


Keyboard controls, make sure to click the window into focus to use:

Press [1] to view at native size.
Press [2] to view at large size.
Press [0] to return to default view.

Press [s] to download and save as PNG.

metadata.name: Alien Stars #18
metadata.description:
This work celebrates the great achievement of the James Webb Space Telescope bringing to us infrared images of the most distant universe so far. Alien stars will soon be unveiled to us in different shapes and forms unknown to date.
Dark mode prevails, light mode rarer, gold mode rarest.
's' key save hi-res .png

metadata.name: contrapuntos #88
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Illusion City #71
metadata.description:
Illusion City reflects the variety of Istanbul by its different and divergent zones, day and night, humid summers and ice cold winters, colorful neighborhoods and giant plazas, its never ending human and vehicle traffic.

This series is an expression of how we experience this city, kind of like a love and hate relationship. The city that is a cradle of civilizations now has become a concrete jungle. Our beautiful city and its citizens are now trying to find their own balance in this state of chaos.

We wanted to express these complex emotions with a long-form generative artwork since it is the most suitable medium to explore every possible combination of emotions we have about our city. 

Best experienced in full screen.

Probabilities;

- 3 pre-made color palettes, 1 generative color palette

- 3 blend modes

- 3 topping placements

- 8 different particle angle compositions

- Several grid sizes and edges

- An intentionally kept in glitch (rare)

In live mode, press ‘s’ to save as .png (2000 x 2666 px )

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, July 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: <iframes> #481
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: the Black Blocks #8
metadata.description: Beauty in asymmetry and random events, combining black boxes, creates an abstract and unexpected atmosphere. The space between black and white invites the eyes to a graphic party full of modern and intimate abstract concepts.
